[4] Singapore
Date: Tue 12 Jun 2007
Source: Today online [edited]
<http://www.todayonline.com/articles/193852.asp>

Another dengue-related death has occurred, making it the 2nd case
this year [2007]. A 63-year-old man living in Hougang died last
Wednesday [6 Jun 2007], after being admitted into Tan Tock Seng
Hospital, the authorities said yesterday [10 Jun 2007]. The man had
sought medical attention for a fever from a general practitioner last
week, but his condition worsened and he was admitted to the hospital,
where he was tested and found to have an acute dengue [virus]
infection. He died from dengue shock syndrome, which also caused the
death of an 85-year-old man in April [2007].
The latest death occurred in a week when dengue infections were on
the rise again (293), compared to 227 cases the week before. The
number of active dengue clusters has also gone up to 54, 4 more than
last week. The most active areas are Jalan Songket, Aroozoo Avenue,
Boon Lay Drive, West Coast Drive, West Coast Road, Ho Ching Road, and
Tao Ching Road.
Some 2014 homes were found to be breeding mosquitoes between January
and May this year [2007] -- an increase of about 80 percent compared
to the same period last year [2006]. In addition, for every 1000
homes inspected by the NEA (National Environment Agency) in April and
May [2007], 6.3 and 5.6 homes respectively were found to be breeding
mosquitoes -- a sharp increase from February and March [2007], when
the figures were less than 2 for every 1000 homes inspected.
So far, 2472 cases of dengue infection have been reported this year
[2007], an 89 percent jump over the same period last year [2006].
Madam Halimah Yacob, the Government Parliamentary Committee Chairman
for Health, said that in spite of the efforts to promote the fight
against dengue, Singaporeans were still "complacent". "When we do
house visits, we have found cases of mosquitoes breeding in the same
homes, even though we have warned them before," she said. "People
still think they are invincible. We need people to understand that it
can really happen to them."
[Byline: Lin Yanqin]
