[6] Brazil
Date: Thu 7 Jun 2007
Source: Diario da Noticia [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.diariodanoticia.com.br/noticia.php?id=1075>

The efficiency of the country in fighting dengue has worsened. In the
first 4 months of the year [2007], the number of cases of this
disease increased 20 percent compared to the number of cases during
the same period in 2006. There were 246 833 patients infected, of
which 288 were DHF (dengue hemorrhagic fever). There were 38 deaths,
between 10 and 15 percent more than in the same period last year
[2006].
Concerned for this increase, a group of consultants from the Pan
American Health Organization (PAHO) will travel to Brazil in July
[2007] to analyze the [government's] plan to combat dengue.
Fabiano Pimenta, acting secretary for Health Surveillance [Ministry
of Health], indicated that the increase in cases this year [2007] is
due to the combination of 2 factors: an increase in the intensity and
duration of rainfall and the explosion of cases in Mato Grosso do
Sul: 68 000 cases, just this year [2007]. "In the state, there have
been a large number of [mosquito] breeding sites, and the people have
no immunity to dengue [virus type] 3. This has produced an explosion
of cases." he observed.
Pimenta recognized, however, that in other localities where the
population was also susceptible to dengue [virus type] 3 the epidemic
could be contained. This was the case in Minas Gerais. "it is an
example that, with good field work and the cooperation of the people,
it is possible to avoid an explosive number of cases," he affirmed.
